{"id":"project-LICHEN-917q","title":"schnorr.rs: Domain separation vulnerability - build_signable lacks dst_addr length prefix","description":"File: rust/lichen-link/src/schnorr.rs
Lines: 186-194

The build_signable function constructs the signed message as:

    fn build_signable(epoch: u8, seqnum: LinkSeqNum, dst_addr: &[u8], inner_payload: &[u8]) -> Vec<u8> {
        let mut buf = Vec::with_capacity(3 + dst_addr.len() + inner_payload.len());
        buf.push(epoch);
        buf.extend_from_slice(&seqnum.to_be_bytes());
        buf.extend_from_slice(dst_addr);
        buf.extend_from_slice(inner_payload);
        buf
    }

Without a length prefix for dst_addr, the same hash is produced for different (dst_addr, payload) combinations when addr_mode changes:

- Frame A: addr_mode=EUI64, dst_addr=0x0102030405060708, payload=0x0A0B
- Frame B: addr_mode=BROADCAST, payload=0x01020304050607080A0B

Both produce identical signed messages: epoch || seqnum || 0x0102030405060708 || 0x0A0B

This is the same vulnerability as project-LICHEN-j7rk but in the Rust implementation.

Fix: Add dst_addr.len() as a prefix byte in build_signable:
    buf.push(dst_addr.len() as u8);
    buf.extend_from_slice(dst_addr);","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T17:11:27.825026Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T17:11:27.825055Z"}
